Struggle for Withdrawal of U.S. Forces from S. Korea Called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The International Liaison Committee for Reunification and Peace in Korea in an appeal issued on Sept. 7, 59 years after the U.S. imperialist aggression forces' occupation of south Korea, called upon all peace-loving and progressive anti-U.S. forces of the world to unite close and turn out in the struggle to force the U.S. to completely pull back its forces and military equipment from south Korea.
 Recalling that the U.S. forces landed on south Korea on Sept. 8, 1945 under the pretext of "disarming the Japanese troops" and proclaimed a military rule, seizing all civil and military rights, the appeal branded their occupation of south Korea as a violation of the sovereignty and independence of the Korean nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For the last 59 years the U.S. troops have been the root cause of unspeakable misfortune and sufferings of the south Korean people. The desire of the south Korean people for socio-political democracy and the ardent will of all the Koreans in the north, south and overseas for the independent and peaceful reunification of Korea can never come true as long as the U.S. forces are present in south Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The security and peace of the people in Korea and those of the countries around it can never be guaranteed so long as the U.S. forces and their modern combat equipment remain in south Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Dismissing the projected "reduction" of the U.S. forces in south Korea as a deceptive farce, the appeal said the U.S. plans to spend 13 billion dollars for its forces in south Korea for the three years to come according to the "arms buildup plan" in a bid to arm its forces with modern military equipment, while cutting down their numerical strength, and then their military potential will grow stronger far from getting weak. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the progressive forces should not harbour even the slightest illusion about the "reduction" of the U.S. forces in south Korea but turn out in the struggle to eliminate the factors of threatening the reunification and peace of Korea and the security and peace of its people and the rest of the world, the appeal noted.

Solidarity Expressed to Struggle of NDFSK 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The Swiss Committee for Supportingb Korea's Reunification sent a letter to the Central Committee of the National Democratic Front of south Korea on August 24 on the occasion of its 35th anniversary.
 The letter said the foundation of the NDFSK was a historic event and brilliant torchlight in the struggle of the south Korean people for national reunification and against the U.S. imperialists. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The committee supports the patriotic struggle of the NDFSK organizations and vanguard fighters to build an independent and democratic society and reunify the country under the banner of the June 15 North-South Joint Declaration and expresses solidarity with it, declared the letter. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It wished the NDFSK greater victory in its noble and patriotic struggle.

Total Abolition of SL Urged 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 5 (KCNA) -- The Democratic Society for the Study of Law in south Korea reportedly issued a statement on Sept. 8 demanding the total abrogation of the "Security Law" (SL).
 The statement said the decision of the Constitutional Court that SL conforms to the constitution and the judgment of the Supreme Court refuting the demand for the repeal of the SL were an infringement upon the people's will for democracy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Criticizing the Grand National Party opposing the abolition of the SL and misleading public opinion, taking advantage of the decision and judgment, the statement strongly demanded it choose to the repeal of the SL, the only way to fully ensure the freedom of idea, conscience and expression. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The society calls for the total abolition of the SL that has trampled upon the human rights and democracy for 56 years and opposes the revision of the criminal law aimed at turning it into a security law, declared the statement.

Russian Army Academic Ensemble Performs for Guests of Honor 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The visiting Russian Army Academic Song and Dance Ensemble Named after Alexandrov gave a performance for the guests of honor at the April 25 House of Culture Tuesday.
 Present there on invitation were Vice-Marshal of the Korean People's Army Kim Il Chol, minister of the People's Armed Forces, Jong Ha Chol, secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea, KPA General Pak Jae Gyong, Kim Jong Ho, chairman of the Central Committee of the General Federation of the Unions of Literature and the Arts of Korea, KPA servicepersons, artistes, working people in the city and military attaches of foreign embassies here. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Among the audience were N.V. Burbyga, deputy director of the Education General Bureau of the Armed Forces of the Russian Federation who is head of the ensemble, Igor Pavlov, military attache of the Russian embassy here, and staff members of the embassy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ensemble clearly showed its feature as an art organization with a long history and tradition. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Russian artistes sang immortal revolutionary paeans "Song of General Kim Il Sung" and "Song of General  Kim Jong Il" with profound feelings, deeply impressing the audience. Their repertoire included male solo and chorus "My Blessed Life" and female solo and chorus "Hero Was 18 Years Old" and other colorful numbers. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 "Just War," "Kalinka" and other Russian songs and "Kazak Cavalrymen Dance" and "Let's Become Seamen" and other dances deeply impressed the audience for the performers' high level of representation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The curtain dropped with chorus of song "Our Friendship Is Everlasting." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A floral basket was presented to the performers in congratulation of their success.

4th Pyongyang International Scientific and Technological Books Fair Closes 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The 4th Pyongyang International Scientific and Technological Books Fair which had been open since September 12 closed.
 The closing ceremony was held at the Grand People's Study House on September 14. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present there were Choe Thae Bok, secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea, Mun Jae Chol, acting chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries who was chairman of the organizing committee of the fair, Jon Yong Jin, vice-chairman of the Korean Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries, Kim Hae Ryong, deputy general director of the Grand People's Study House, officials concerned, men of the press, scientists and technicians. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Delegations and delegates from different countries, foreign diplomatic envoys and embassy officials, representatives of international organizations and members of their missions here were also present. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A letter to leader Kim Jong Il from the participants in the fair was adopted at the ceremony. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Donation certificates were awarded to the organizations which had donated books. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Mun Jae Chol in his closing address stated that it was the consistent stand of the DPRK to promote the common prosperity of humankind and develop friendly relations with the world people through scientific and technological exchange and cooperation. The DPRK will as ever make energetic efforts to bolster scientific and technological exchange and cooperation with different countries of the world, true to the idea of independence, peace and friendship, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 While the fair was open delegations and delegates swapped their achievements and experience in the fields of science, technology and the press and views on boosting cooperation and exchange among them, deepening sentiments of friendship.

Anti-U.S. Exhibition in Seoul
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The Reunification Solidarity and other civic and social organizations of south Korea reportedly co-sponsored an exhibition under the motto "Let us achieve national independence through anti-U.S. struggle" in Seoul from Sept. 9 to 11.
 On display at the exhibition in chronological order were photos showing crimes committed by U.S. soldiers in south Korea. It opened upon the lapse of 59 years since the occupation of south Korea by the U.S. imperialists. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Yun Ji Hye, director of the Information Department of the Solidarity, said the exhibition was opened to build up broader public opinion about the unnecessariness of the U.S. forces' presence in south Korea, stating that it meant the beginning of the struggle for their withdrawal. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Citizens said they could see clearly the true colors of the U.S. forces through the pictures. They gave vent to their resentment, saying: "After all, the United States was not our friendly nation".

Letter to Kim Jong Il from Participants in Internatl Books Fair
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The participants in the 4th Pyongyang International Scientific and Technological Books Fair presented a letter to leader Kim Jong Il on Sept.14.
 The letter said that the fair which drew 27 bodies of various countries and international organizations offered an important occasion in strengthening the exchange and cooperation in science and technology among countries. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK adopted it as its strategic line of building a great prosperous powerful nation to attach importance to science and technology and has worked hard to implement it and thus made big achievements in scientific and technical research and in training men of ability, the letter said, adding: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Seeing this reality we became confident that your country will proudly rank itself among the world's scientifically and technologically advanced nations in the near future. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The letter expressed the willingness to strengthen the scientific and technological exchange and cooperation with the DPRK and render positive cooperation in the efforts to put the Pyongyang International Scientific and Technological Books Fair at the world's level.

Chairman of Russian Federation Council Visits Kim Il Sung University
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- Sergei Mikhailovich Mironov, chairman of the Federation Council of Russia, and his entourage visited Kim Il Sung University on Sept. 14.
 They looked round the gift museum and the classroom where leader Kim Jong Il studied. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then the chairman gave a lecture on the present political situation in Russia and the issue of developing the Russia-DPRK relations before teachers and students of the university. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He said he was pleased to visit Kim Il Sung University where Kim Jong Il, the leader of the DPRK, studied and which is a center for scientific education and a most prestigious university. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He recalled that Russian President V. V. Putin and Chairman of the DPRK National Defence Commission Kim Jong Il have shown deep concern for the development of the traditional relations of friendship and good neighborliness between Russia and the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He pointed out that Korean students obtained most excellent results by displaying high ability at the 11th International Student Russian Olympiad held in Moscow in June. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Expressing belief that the good neighborly and mutually beneficial Russia-DPRK relations of friendship and cooperation would steadily grow stronger, he wished the Korean people greater success and prosperity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The chairman donated books and video cassettes to the university.

Tractor "Chollima-2000" Proves Effective
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The Kum Song Tractor Plant of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea is manufacturing tractor "Chollima-2000".
 The new model, with a hydraulic steering wheel and direct jet diesel engine, has a big pulling power while consuming a small amount of fuel. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The vibration and sound of the engine in operation are as low as motorcar. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All the accessories of the tractor are precisely processed and assembled with the help of ultra-modern technology. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The tractor is easy and convenient to operate. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Its working speed is 7 kilometers per hour and turning radius 3 meters. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Leader Kim Jong Il watched the tractor in operation during his field guidance to a farm and said that it was a good and well-shaped tractor.

Credentials to Kim Yong Nam from Norwegian Ambassador
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, received credentials from Arild
Brastad, Norwegian ambassador e. p. to the DPRK, at the Mansudae Assembly Hall on Sept. 15. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand was Kung Sok Ung, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 After receiving the credentials, the president had a conversation with the ambassador.

1st International Martial Art Games Open
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, September 15 (KCNA) -- The first International Martial Art Games opened with splendour in Pyongyang today.
 At least 400 practitioners and delegates from more than 40 countries will compete in the games. The games will offer an important occasion in promoting the friendship and solidarity among countries, nations and martial art practitioners and prove to be a grand assembly for exchanging skills among them. 
 The games will include competitions in Korea's orthodox martial art Taekwon-do, martial arts of other countries and nations and demonstration matches. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Jang Ung, president of the International Taekwon-do Federation who is chairman of the International Martial Art Games Committee, made an address which was followed by the hoisting of the flag of the games. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Pak Pong Ju, premier of the DPRK Cabinet, in his congratulatory address said that the first historic international martial art games be held in the DPRK would greatly please and encourage the people of the DPRK in their efforts to achieve national reunification and build a great prosperous powerful socialist nation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He expressed belief that the games would prove successful in line with the idea of independence, peace, friendship and solidarity. The DPRK will extend positive support and solidarity to the games and strengthen friendship and solidarity with the martial art practitioners and progressive people of the world, he concluded. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then the floor was taken by Mac Harb, president of IMAG. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The first flame of the martial art games was lit in Pyongyang and the curtain of the games went up here, he said, adding that this would offer an important occasion in developing martial art. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The IMAGC will respect the noble idea of international martial art and exert all its efforts to strengthen and develop it, he added.  Present at the ceremony were Mun Jae Dok, chairman of the Korean Physical Culture and Sports Guidance Commission, Hwang Pong Yong, chairman of the Korean Martial Art Federation who is chairman of the Korean Taekwon-do Committee, Jong Jae Hun, secretary general of the International Martial Art Games Committee who is chairman of the organizing committee of the first International Martial Art Games, officials concerned, diplomatic envoys of different countries here, practitioners and delegates from various countries and regions, guests of honor, overseas Koreans and foreigners staying in the DPRK.
